Breast Cancer Wisconsin (Diagnostic) Data Set¶

by Yosef Cohen¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

About the data set:¶

The data set is from : https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/breast-cancer-wisconsin-data
(The next line are from the description on Kaggle site:)
Description

Features are computed from a digitized image of a fine needle aspirate (FNA) of a breast mass. They describe characteristics of the cell nuclei present in the image. n the 3-dimensional space is that described in: [K. P. Bennett and O. L. Mangasarian: "Robust Linear Programming Discrimination of Two Linearly Inseparable Sets", Optimization Methods and Software 1, 1992, 23-34].

This database is also available through the UW CS ftp server: ftp ftp.cs.wisc.edu cd math-prog/cpo-dataset/machine-learn/WDBC/

Also can be found on UCI Machine Learning Repository: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Breast+Cancer+Wisconsin+%28Diagnostic%29

Attribute Information:

1) ID number
2) Diagnosis (M = malignant, B = benign)
3-32)

Ten real-valued features are computed for each cell nucleus:

a) radius (mean of distances from center to points on the perimeter)
b) texture (standard deviation of gray-scale values)
c) perimeter
d) area
e) smoothness (local variation in radius lengths)
f) compactness (perimeter^2 / area - 1.0)
g) concavity (severity of concave portions of the contour)
h) concave points (number of concave portions of the contour)
i) symmetry
j) fractal dimension ("coastline approximation" - 1)

The mean, standard error and "worst" or largest (mean of the three largest values) of these features were computed for each image, resulting in 30 features. For instance, field 3 is Mean Radius, field 13 is Radius SE, field 23 is Worst Radius.

All feature values are recoded with four significant digits.

Missing attribute values: none

Class distribution: 357 benign, 212 malignant

In [19]:
for col in columns:
    fig, (ax1,ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2,figsize = (23,8))
    pal = ['orange', 'blue']
    sns.kdeplot(ax=ax1, data=df_small, x=col, hue="diagnosis",fill=True,palette=pal)
    sns.boxplot(ax=ax2, x="diagnosis", y=col, data=df_small,palette=pal)
    ax1.set(title=f"{col} overlapping malingnant and benign",xlabel=f"{col}",ylabel="count")
    ax2.set(title=f"{col} overlapping malingnant and benign",xlabel=f"{col}",ylabel="count")

from this plots my conclusion is:¶

1. there is a overlap in all the parameters, but the overlap in some of them is small enough that we could find parameters to distinguish between malingnant and benign.
2. the good variables to distinguish are:
    * all the size variables - radius, area, perimeter.
    * compactness
    * concavity
    * concave points
3. variables which are not good enough are:
    * smoothness
    * symmetry
    * fractal dimetion

two variables correlations:¶

lets see correlations with heat map:¶

In [20]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))
ax = sns.heatmap(df_small.corr(), annot=True,cmap="YlGnBu")

we see strong correlations too between :¶

  • perimeter,radius and area corr are approximaly 1, what says that we could refer them as one "size" variable!
  • concave points_mean - perimeter_mean (0.85)
  • compactness_mean - concavity_mean (0.88)
  • concavity_mean - concave points_mean (0.92)

and what about the "worst" variables ? are they proportional to the normal ?¶

we see that the most of the correlation pretty high, between worst and normal.¶

  • radius - 0.97
  • texture - 0.91
  • smoothness - 0.87
  • concavity - 0.88
  • compactness - 0.87
  • concave_points_mean - 0.91 #### simmetry and fractal dimention :
  • simmetry - 0.7
  • fractal - 0.77 #### (but we say before that simmetry and fractal are not good indicator to distinguish between B & M) #### the meaning is that we could use the regular variables (radius, texture,smoothness,concavity, concave_points_mean) because they are in proportion to the "worst" variables and we don't need the "worst" variables to predict M & B.

Conclusion:¶

  • I think that the best predictable variables are:
    1. size variables (radius,perimeter,area) - they are proportional so i prefer them as 1 variable.
    2. compactness
    3. concave points_mean & concavity - they are proportional too.
  • the combination of this 3 could predict if the tumor is malingnant or benign
